entry.title: Disable libgnome-keyring in default builds
entry.content:
The libsecret backend was intended to replace the libgnome-keyring

backend. The libsecret backend was implemented in March 2015, but

the libgnome-keyring backend was kept around as a fallback since 5%

of users were still using it [1]. Now in 2023, gnome-keyring is no

longer available in any distro we support.



Currently the inclusion of gnome-keyring is preventing upgrading

the Debian sysroots [2] so this CL finally turns the build flag off.

A followup CL will remove the gnome-keyring code.



[1] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=355223#c17

[2] https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/linux-rel/1428857/overview

entry.title: Remove spurious visual data sync updates.
entry.content:
- Fix a spurious visual data sync update when dragging a group into a new window. We used to call OnGroupClosedInTabStrip followed by OnGroupOpenedInTabStrip, which meant we had to do an update of the visual data after re-opening it to get the header in the right state. Now, we just leave the connection intact the whole time, by going through the listener hierarchy and respecting pause state, so the header starts in the correct visual state in the new window.



- Fix a spurious visual data sync update when opening a saved group in the tabstrip. We used to create the local group, start listening to it, then update the visual data, creating a sync update; now we update the visual data before we start listening.



- Ignore no-op visual data updates across the board to catch anything I missed and/or anything new that gets introduced later.

entry.title: [A11y] Remove subtrees of nodes removed from flat tree.
entry.content:
Create a method called RemoveSubtreeWhenSafe() that removes subtrees as

soon as it is safe to traverse the flat tree, so that there can be no

orphaned objects left in the cache.



Specifically, "when safe" means:

1) If CanSafelyUseFlatTraversal() returns true, do it now (flat

traversal is not forbidden and there are no pending slot assignments

2) Otherwise, do it towards the beginning of a11y's clean layout

processing. This may be later than necessary -- we may consider having

a special callback that occurs as soon as flat traversal is safe.

entry.title: Implement WebView client-side feature overrides
entry.content:
Currently, overriding a feature are implemented as a map of feature name and override states and this map is generated using map emplace. It results in the first override wins when there are a couple of mechanisms to override a feature.



There are three ways to override a feature in order: 1) command-line override -> 2) Finch override -> 3) default override.



Android WebView modifies the command line flags during startup when it needs overrides the feature which is different from Android Chrome. This leads those features can't be overridden by Finch. In other words, it's hard to experiment those feature on Android WebView.



This CL implements a new API in PlatformFieldTrials, which allows platform to add extra overrides between Finch overrides and default override.



This CL also move the first feature user case UserAgentClientHint into the new implemented API. We can migrate all similar features to the new API on Android WebView once we verify this new mechanism.

entry.title: IndexedDB: avoid copy of value bytes
entry.content:
Remove one copy operation when sending IDB values over Mojo. This will

only affect data that's up to but not more than 64k in size (over 64k

gets stored as a Blob).



On my cloudtop, this had zero measurable impact on performance for

data of size 50KB. When I ratcheted the data size up to 1MB (and

disabled value wrapping) there was a small but measurable improvement

of about 0.5 ms per read operation. I measured this both by

adding `base::TimeTicks` in the code, as well as with these

benchmarks[1] (adding my own for 50KB).



Even though this yields no measurable improvement given current

parameters, I think this change is worthwhile because:



a) some devices that are less powerful than my workstation may see

a benefit

b) *memory* usage should be reduced by a small but known amount

c) we may remove value wrapping if we switch from leveldb to SQLite



[1] https://github.com/zeroliu/indexeddb_playground

entry.title: Remove check for isTabStateInitialized from TabModelSelectorProfileSupplier.
entry.content:
isTabStateInitialized indicates that all the tabs have been read from

disk and have been populated into the TabModel.



For users with many, many tabs, this can be considerably after the

initial tab has loaded and a the user can interact with Chrome.



The Profile object is passed into TabModelImpl during the constructor

here:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/tabmodel/TabModelImpl.java;drc=56163aa1366cc89f595e343649ff6743b6feddc5;l=94



For the incognito tab model, it was updated to have a valid profile

after setActive is called here:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/tabmodel/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/tabmodel/IncognitoTabModelImpl.java;drc=d0e09465fb2ccf68583393af1730cd9095461bb7;l=274



setActive being called from TabModelSelectorImpl:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:chrome/android/java/src/org/chromium/chrome/browser/tabmodel/TabModelSelectorBase.java;drc=797705faabe0d735dc99664db6db6a9320d75511;l=100



This now listens to notifyChanged and will check for the profile more

often, but the ObservableSupplier will suppress duplicate updates.



This should result in the Profile being "immediately" available in

most cases.

entry.title: Never force a break before when we're already inside the node.
entry.content:
When resuming a node after a fragmentainer break, ignore break-before

values, since we're obviously not *before* it anymore (since we're

*inside*). We used to end up in an infinite loop, until out of memory,

not making any fragmentation progress. This was caused by monolithic

content, which, when printing, may take up space on subsequent pages.

This tricked us into thinking that it was a good place to insert a

forced break before the node we were resuming, since we were not at the

beginning of the page.

entry.title: shortcuts: Show correct results when query is single character
entry.content:
This CL is doing two main things:

- On backend, adjust search relevance threshold from default of 0.64

to 0.4

- On frontend, request 15 results instead of 5, and then cap the number

after filtering to ensure that we always show 5 results when possible.

Before, we'd filter the requested 5 results, so if any results were

disabled, we'd show fewer than 5 results even if there were more

matching accelerators.



DEMO:

https://screencast.googleplex.com/cast/NTIzNjc0MTI0NzA3NDMwNHxiNTI4Yzc3My1iZA

Left side is before, right side is after.

As you can see, the "after" search is a lot more broad, matching on

queries that contain a fuzzier match. I think it's an improvement, but

I'm open to feedback. Unfortunately, `relevance_threshold` is our only

lever / input into the search system, so it's a trade-off between single

character searches and overly-lax fuzzy matching.



I've also added additional comments to search_concept_registry.cc

to make things clearer.



I've also added frontend + backend tests for these changes.

entry.title: [omnibox][cr23] Fix cursor position test for SS height.
entry.content:
https://screenshot.googleplex.com/Bz5jWYp5HkhADMB



crrev.com/c/4581107 launched omnibox SS height, increasing the omnibox

height from 28px to 34px.



chromeOS had some rounding issues, where it actually used a 29px omnibox

instead of a 28px omnibox. It also uses a 17px cursor height instead of

16px like linux.



There's a test

`AccessibilityHighlightsBrowserTest.CaretHighlightOmnibox` that checks

the cursor is vertically centered in the omnibox. Due to the rounding

issues on chromeOS, it ended up being 1px off after increasing the

omnibox height to 34px. So that CL also updated the test to expect the

cursor to be centered at 1px less than the center of the omnibox.



But this broke the test on linux, since linux didn't have the rounding

issue that chromeOS did.



So this CL updates the test to expect the cursor to be EITHER centered

OR 1px off from center.



Bug: 1416351, 1453711

entry.title: Update ZOOM filter to store lens bounds
entry.content:
The SkMagnifierImageFilter implementation that provided the rendering

for the ZOOM cc::FilterOperation did not follow the SkImageFilter

contract. Specifically it didn't really respond to the active canvas

matrix, and applied its effects to whatever image it's input filter

produced. It *should* have had a well-defined geometry to control the

required input and expected output, as well as be able to properly

adapt to the canvas matrix.



In chromium:1425773, these issues finally became visible when the

ZOOM filter was combined with a backdrop offset, a new magnifier

widget, and used on devices that could rotate their screen. To address

them, an entirely new Magnifier filter was added to Skia that takes

the lens bounds as a parameter, and has improved logic for zooming

when requested content is unavailable (e.g. offscreen).



This CL updates cc::MagnifierPaintFilter to take the lens bounds and

call the new Skia factory. It has logic to switch between nearest

neighbor sampling (the historic behavior) and bilinear (much higher

quality for non-integer scale factors).



Because of how cc::Layers specify their filter operations, I opted to

not add lens bounds to the ZOOM filter operation; it's behavior is to

use the layer's bounds as the lens bounds once the compositor has to

handle it in RenderSurfaceFilters::BuildImageFilters.



Bug: 1425773, 642536, skia:9378
